\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 NIDEVER TRANSCRIPTION
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
Soon after his return Sparks went up to Monterey to see a new schooner that was being built by a Mexican, at that place. The schooner's name was to be "Peor es Nada";' of about 20 tons burthen. He charted her for a trip on the Lower
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  California coast; a man by name of Charley Hubbard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 98}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  being put in command by the owners.
\par 
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 Sparks was accompanied by Burton and a hunter by name of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 Dye." }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 They returned about Sept., I think, having made a very poor hunt owing to their failure to agree among\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
 themselves. They got, I believe, only 25 skins when they should have secured }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 200 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 at least, as the otter were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 plenty, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 the N. W. Indians not having been there for some years. The N. W. Indians did hunt along that coast afterward and killed a great many otte
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
r. In the following Oct. after the return from the Leeward, as Lower Cal. Was called, Sparks went over to San Nicolas Island.100 Others accompanied Sparks and among them Williams,' of the Chino ranch in Los Angeles Co., and who was with me in the Mts.; he
,\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
 with Col. Bean, having shown the white feather in our first engagement with the Indians, on the Ark. River. They removed the Indians, some 17 or 18 men, women and children, from this Island to San Pedro, and thence to Los Angeles and San Gabriel. I have 
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 h\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
eard from Sparks an account of the affair but do not remember the details distinctly. Some one in Los Angeles authorized the removal of these Indians, the last of the inhabitants of San Nicolas, but with what object I do not know, and cannot remember if I
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
have ever heard. I am sure Williams had an interest in the matter, as he afterwards took one of the Indian women to live with. Having got the Indians together on the Island, they took them to the beach and put them on board the schooner. They then took th
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 e\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
m direct to San Pedro having, however, left one Indian woman on the Island. Of the exact manner in which she was left I do not now remember, but am under the impression that Sparks told me that it happened in this way. Having got all of the Indians down o
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 n\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  the beach, one of the women wanted to go back to their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
rancheria }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f31506\insrsid8924643\charrsid12137950 \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
for her child that had been left behind, which she was allowed to do. While she was absent, a strong wind sprang up and, fearing for the safety of the schooner should they wait longer, they \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
put off from shore and ran before the wind. Arriving safely at San Pedro, the Indians were landed, from whence they proceeded to Los Angeles, where a portion of them remained; the rest being taken to San Gabriel. One of the Indians, however, a large power
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 f\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
ul man, was left at San Pedro. He lived on the beach among the hunters, where I saw him several times. I think he was one of the most muscular men, white or Indian, I ever saw. He was but a little above the medium height, heavy set and full and broad shou
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 l\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
ders and chest. He was partly foolish, from a fracture of the skull received in a fight with the N. W. Indians, but he was perfectly harmless and invariably good humored. He was always willing to work, cheerfully performing the most fatiguing tasks, oftti
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 m\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
es without being solicited. If a boat was to be hauled ashore he would frequently rush into the water, catch hold of the boat and run it high and dry on the beach, a feat that usually required from 3 to 4 ordinary men to perform. I also saw him take under
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
his arm and bring a considerable distance to the shore a spotted seal that had been shot from shore. This seal would weigh not less than 300 to 400 lbs., besides being very awkward to handle. It would have required 3 men at least to bring it ashore. I nev
\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 e\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 
r heard what became of him. The schooner "Peor es Nada" was ordered to report at Monterey immediately to take a cargo of timber to S. F. and thus no time was given them to return to the Island for this woman, although I think it was the intention of the s
